	The sequence of triangle numbers is generated by adding the natural numbers.
	So the 7th triangle number would be \( 1 \mathplus 2 \mathplus 3 \mathplus 4 \mathplus 5 \mathplus 6 \mathplus 7 \equal 28 \).
	The first ten terms would be:
	\begin{equation*}
		\numlist{1;3;6;10;15;21;28;36;45;55;\dots}
	\end{equation*}

	Let us list the factors of the first seven triangle numbers:
	\begin{center}\ttfamily%
		\medskip%
		\begin{tabular}{r@{\ :\ }l}
			\bfseries  1 & \num{1} \\%
			\bfseries  3 & \numlist{1;3}\\%
			\bfseries  6 & \numlist{1;2;3;6}\\%
			\bfseries 10 & \numlist{1;2;5;10}\\%
			\bfseries 15 & \numlist{1;3;5;15}\\%
			\bfseries 21 & \numlist{1;3;7;21}\\%
			\bfseries 28 & \numlist{1;2;4;7;14;28}\\%
		\end{tabular}
		\medskip%
	\end{center}
	We can see that 28 is the first triangle number to have over five divisors.

	What is the value of the first triangle number to have over five hundred divisors?
